</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="_fn_p53"><p>WR = water restricted, FR = food restricted, NR = non-restricted, (+) = suppression, (−) = disrupted suppression, (+/−) = transient suppression</p></div></div></section><p id="P34">When evaluated under non-restricted conditions, the suppressive effects of LiCl, morphine, and cocaine, at every dose tested, induced significant avoidance of the saccharin CS after just one or two taste-drug pairings. Thus, there were no differences in the suppressive effects across the compounds unless a restriction state was imposed. As such, the disrupted suppressive effect of morphine and cocaine following restriction cannot be attributed to learning deficits or to dose, per se, because these interpretations would have predicted a similar pattern of behavior regardless of restriction state. Clearly, restriction enhanced the drive to consume saccharin. This enhanced drive was sufficient to override the suppressive effects of cocaine and morphine at lower doses, but was less effective in overriding the suppressive effects of LiCl, even at extremely low doses.</p>
<p id="P35">Relative to the non-restricted condition, water restriction reduced the suppressive effects of both cocaine and morphine on saccharin intake. Thus, even at doses found highly effective in the non-restricted state (see <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>), both morphine and cocaine were rendered either completely ineffective or marginally effective when evaluated in the water restricted state. Water restriction also reduced the suppressive effects of LiCl, but in this case, saccharin-LiCl pairings still led to a fairly robust, approximate 50% reduction, in CS intake. Again, of the three drugs tested, LiCl was most resistant to the disruptive effect of water restriction on drug-induced suppression of CS intake.</p>
<p id="P36">Food restriction resulted in the most complicated pattern of responding across the dose response function for each drug and was less conclusive than water restriction at differentiating between the compounds. While saccharin is sweet, it contains no calories. Without calories, the saccharin may not be as rewarding to a food restricted rat as it is to a water restricted rat. Nevertheless, the efficacy of each drug compound to support conditioned avoidance of the saccharin CS was reduced by food restriction and LiCl was the most resistant to this reduction. Why food restriction disrupted avoidance of saccharin at the lowest dose of LiCl, but enhanced the efficacy of the lowest dose of morphine is unclear. However, the unusual effects of food restriction on morphine-induced suppression were not consistent across the dose response and trials, as the next two intermediate low doses (1.5 and 3 mg/kg) were completely ineffective, and 5 mg/kg actually produced a reinforcement effect by trial 8. In fact, in the food restricted condition, morphine did not suppress intake of a saccharin CS consistently except at the lowest and highest doses. This pattern of transient suppression for the 5, 15, and 30 mg/kg doses (i.e., the establishment of suppression that gradually dissipated) was unique to the food restricted, morphine-injected rats and, therefore, is difficult to explain. On the one hand, if tolerance alone were to explain the waning suppressive effects of morphine (<a href="#R67" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R67">Siegel, Parker et al. 1995</a>) then it would be expected to occur equally across the restriction conditions and at the lowest dose in the food restricted rats. Moreover, if the transient suppression was an effect of food restriction alone, then a similar pattern of suppression would be expected in the food restricted rats that were injected with cocaine. While it is well known that food restriction enhances the rewarding properties of sweets and drugs of abuse (<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">Carr, Kim et al. 2000</a>; <a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">Carroll, Campbell et al. 2001</a>), and reduces the threshold for rewarding electrical brain stimulation in the lateral hypothalamus (<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">Carr 2002</a>), it remains unclear why food restriction appeared to enhance tolerance to the suppressive effect of morphine, but not cocaine, across trials. Some clarity may be gained by the evidence that food restriction alters the expression of endogenous opioid peptides (as well as many other peptides responsible for maintaining energy balance) that are known to mediate the rewarding properties of sweets (<a href="#R59" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R59">Pecina and Berridge 1995</a>; <a href="#R43" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R43">Kelley, Bakshi et al. 2002</a>; <a href="#R60" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R60">Pecina and Berridge 2005</a>). Thus, it is possible that sensitization and tolerance to morphine could progress uniquely when animals are food deprived, particularly in a model where the effect of the drug is measured by intake of a sweet cue.</p>
<p id="P37">Perhaps the simplest explanation for the potent avoidance of saccharin intake when the rats are not deprived of either water or food is that the hedonic value of the saccharin solution is reduced. Therefore, the motivation to consume saccharin is also reduced and, as such, is more readily avoided in anticipation of drug effects. Depriving a rat of water or food, then, increases the hedonic valence of saccharin and drives its consumption. The relative motivational apathy inherent to the non-restricted state would be expected to facilitate the devaluation of saccharin induced by pairings with either drugs of abuse or LiCl. Nevertheless, the heightened motivational states of restriction appear to more effectively override the expression of saccharin avoidance induced by cocaine and morphine then by LiCl. The prominent rightward shift in the dose response curve for both morphine and cocaine, but not LiCl, by water restriction extends support for the idea that morphine and cocaine mediate avoidance of a saccharin CS by a different mechanism than LiCl. Thus, despite our best efforts to include “matched” doses of drug, the illness induced by LiCl may simply differ from the suppressive effects of morphine and cocaine. For example, with LiCl, the US may only need to reach a detectable threshold in order to induce avoidance of an associated taste cue. Once the US is detected, a LiCl-induced CTA will occur in spite of restriction state because the primary function of the CS is to avoid illness by avoiding the illness-associated tastant and, of course, this must hold fast even when in need of water or food. In contrast, because malaise is not at the core of morphine- and cocaine-induced suppression of CS intake, the drug doses need to be not only detectable, but also of sufficient motivational strength to elicit the formation of an opposing conditioned compensatory response or to shift the animal out of saccharin-seeking behavior and toward drug-seeking behavior. This is the case even for very low doses of the drug when examined in a non-restricted state suggesting that the hedonic value of saccharin may compete with drugs of abuse under certain parameters (<a href="#R48" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R48">Lenoir, Serre et al. 2007</a>). When water or food restricted, however, the drug must be even more potent to support a reduction in intake of the sweet saccharin cue. In accordance with this view and outside of the complexities of drug effects, food restriction also prevents sucrose-induced suppression of intake of a weak sucrose cue in the anticipatory contrast paradigm (<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">Flaherty, Grigson et al. 1991</a>; <a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">Flaherty 1996</a>).</p>
<p id="P38">As alluded to above, recent data suggest that aversive taste reactivity can arise in the “CTA” paradigm for at least two very different reasons. With strictly aversive agents (e.g., LiCl, radiation, intense magnetic fields), the parsimonious interpretation is that gapes are dependent on the known illness inducing properties of the US. When the US has a complex mix of rewarding, addictive, and aversive effects, however, that parsimonious interpretation is not adequate. Currently, the only paradigm known to produce aversive taste reactivity to a saccharin cue that predicts a drug of abuse like cocaine is when the taste cue is intra-orally delivered over a relatively long CS access period prior to drug administration (<a href="#R76" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R76">Wheeler, Twining, et al., 2008</a>; <a href="#R72" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R72">Wheeler, Aragona et al. 2011</a>). As described, the magnitude of the aversive taste reactivity is the single-best predictor of a short latency to self-administer the first cocaine infusion, rapid self-administration rates during the first 10 minutes of the session (i.e., “load up”), total number of infusions, and the willingness to work for the drug on a progressive ratio schedule of reinforcement (<a href="#R76" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R76">Wheeler, Twining et al. 2008</a>; <a href="#R72" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R72">Wheeler, Aragona et al. 2011</a>; <a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">Colechio and Grigson 2014</a>; <a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">Colechio, Imperio et al. 2014</a>). These findings make the prototypical taste aversion hypothesis untenable, as instrumental behaviors are uniformly punished by LiCl administration – rats will not “self-administer” a drug that induces illness and certainly not with increasing rapidity and in copious amounts. The authors conclude that, in the anticipation of drug, the saccharin cue induces a negative affect state (e.g., cue elicited craving/withdrawal) and, thereby, reduces the palatability of the saccharin cue (Wheeler, Twining, et al., <a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">Grigson, Twining et al. 2008</a>; <a href="#R76" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R76">2008</a>). This interpretation is consistent with the finding that a sweet taste can be conditioned to elicit aversive taste reactivity when it has been associated with naloxone-precipitated withdrawal in morphine dependent rats (<a href="#R50" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R50">McDonald, Parker et al. 1997</a>).</p>
<p id="P39">Despite decades of research on conditioned taste avoidance induced by morphine, cocaine, and LiCl, it was not possible before now to evaluate the effect of restriction state on the individual dose response functions of these drugs, let alone to compare them directly to each other. This is mostly because laboratories, understandably, use different testing parameters, making a comparative analysis quite difficult. Here, the experiments were conducted using standardized procedures and parameters that differed only with respect to the dose and drug employed and, thus, allowed for a reasonable comparative analysis across drug compounds, doses, and restriction states. It should be noted however that, while this analysis is extensive, it is by no means exhaustive. Although we were able to test all three restriction states across seven doses of both LiCl and morphine, we were unable to test two of the cocaine doses (i.e., 15 and 40 mg/kg) in the non-restricted state due to logistics and resources. We chose not to conduct these costly studies because avoidance of the cocaine-paired saccharin cue already is maximal with the 10 mg/kg dose of cocaine when tested in the non-restricted state. However, future studies could incorporate additional drugs of abuse (e.g., heroin, alcohol, nicotine, etc.) and doses into the analysis and sex differences would be an interesting variable to investigate. Suppression of saccharin intake by cocaine (<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">Cason and Grigson 2013</a>), morphine (<a href="#R42" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R42">Jenney, Schroy et al. in prep</a>), and LiCl (<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">Foy and Foy 2003</a>) is attenuated in female rats compared with male rats and it would be informative to evaluate the influence of restriction state in female rats and compare it with the current data set.</p>
<p id="P40">In conclusion, the results in the current manuscript showed that the suppressive effects of lower doses of morphine and cocaine were attenuated or abolished when the rats were either hungry or thirsty. LiCl, on the other hand, remained a potent suppresser of saccharin intake even at very low doses under both food restricted and water restricted conditions. This pattern of data suggests that different mechanisms mediate suppression of CS intake by LiCl and by drugs of abuse such as morphine and cocaine. While attenuated by food and water restriction, the suppressive effects of morphine also differed qualitatively from those of cocaine. Finally, it should be pointed out that lesion studies have dissociated not only LiCl and drug-induced suppression of intake of a saccharin cue (<a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">Grigson, Lyuboslavsky et al. 2000</a>; <a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">Geddes, Han et al. 2008</a>), but also the suppressive effects of a drug of abuse from those of a sweet sucrose reward (<a href="#R53" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R53">Nyland, Alexander et al. 2012</a>). Drug-induced suppression of intake of a gustatory cue, then, is a seemingly unitary and complex phenomenon involving the comparison of a natural reward cue with a drug of abuse that is anticipated in the near future and modulated by the current state of need. This is a critical model for further study, as reduced responding for the natural reward predicts individual vulnerability for drug-seeking and drug-taking in rats (<a href="#R78" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R78">Wise, Yokel et al. 1976</a>; <a href="#R34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R34">Grigson and Twining 2002</a>; <a href="#R76" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R76">Wheeler, Twining et al. 2008</a>; <a href="#R71" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R71">Twining, Bolan et al. 2009</a>; <a href="#R72" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R72">Wheeler, Aragona et al. 2011</a>; <a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">Colechio and Grigson 2014</a>; <a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">Colechio, Imperio et al. 2014</a>; <a href="#R41" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R41">Imperio and Grigson 2015</a>) and in humans (<a href="#R77" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R77">Wilson, Delgado et al. 2014</a>).</p></section><section id="floats-group1" class="floats-group"><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX1"><h2 class="obj_head">Highlights.</h2>
<ul id="L1" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p>We analyzed the effect of restriction state on drug-induced suppression.</p></li>
<li><p>Cocaine efficacy was decreased by water and food restriction.</p></li>
<li><p>Morphine efficacy was decreased by water and food restriction.</p></li>
<li><p>LiCl was the most resistant to the disruptive effects of water or food restriction.</p></li>
</ul></section></section><section id="S22" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS</h2>
<p>The research was supported by the National Institutes of Health, National Institute of Drug Addiction [Grant DA009815].</p></section><section id="fn-group1" class="fn-group"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Footnotes</h2>
